Double Entry Day Book


0) The Accounting “Physics” Your Software Must Respect
Think of accounting like laws of physics:
✅ LAW 1: Money never disappears
It only moves between accounts.
Example:
If Cash increases → something else must decrease or income must increase.
✅ LAW 2: Every transaction is always a “transfer”
Even if user thinks it’s “just payment”, internally it’s:
From Account → To Account
Example:
Salary paid = Money moved from Cash → Salary Expense.
✅ LAW 3: Debit/Credit is NOT positive/negative
Debit = left side
Credit = right side
That’s it.
Whether it increases or decreases depends on account type.
✅ Assets/Expenses increase on Debit
✅ Liabilities/Income/Equity increase on Credit
________________________________________
1) What Your Software is REALLY Building
Your software is building a mini accounting database like this:
✅ Ledger master = “Where money can sit”
✅ Voucher = “One event that moved money”
✅ Voucher lines = “The legs of the movement”
✅ Reports = “Summaries of all movements”
So don’t think “Daybook = list of cash entries”
Think:
✅ Daybook = raw journal
________________________________________
2) Chart of Accounts (COA) — The Brain of Your Software
Most people underestimate this.
Your system becomes powerful only when COA is clean.
✅ 2.1 Ledger Types (Nature)
Each ledger must belong to only ONE nature:
•	ASSET
•	LIABILITY
•	INCOME
•	EXPENSE
•	EQUITY
✅ Why nature matters?
Because your reports depend on it:
✅ P&L uses: INCOME + EXPENSE
✅ Balance Sheet uses: ASSET + LIABILITY + EQUITY
✅ Trial Balance uses everything
________________________________________
✅ 2.2 Group vs Ledger (Professional structure)
Don’t store nature directly in ledger always.
Instead:
✅ ledger_groups table:
•	Current Assets
•	Bank
•	Direct Income
•	Indirect Expense
•	Duties & Taxes
•	Loans (Liability)
•	Capital (Equity)
Then each group has a “nature”.
This gives you Tally style reports.
________________________________________
✅ 2.3 Normal Side (Helper only)
Every ledger can have a normal balance field.
•	Assets/Expenses → DR normal
•	Liabilities/Income/Equity → CR normal
⚠️ This is not a fixed Dr/Cr for posting
It’s only for default suggestions and running balance display.
________________________________________
3) Voucher System — The Engine Core
A voucher is your atomic transaction record.
✅ 3.1 Voucher Header is the “container”
Header stores:
•	Voucher number (human)
•	Voucher ID (UUID)
•	Date
•	Voucher type
•	Status (Draft/Posted/Reversed)
•	Narration
•	Branch
•	Created by
✅ Why totals must be stored in header?
Because it creates fast validations and fast reporting filters.
________________________________________
✅ 3.2 Voucher Lines are the “legs”
Each line must be:
✅ One ledger
✅ One side only (DR or CR)
✅ One amount only
✅ Optional party link
A line should NEVER contain both debit and credit.
________________________________________
✅ 3.3 Why your “line structure” should be side + amount
Instead of:
•	debit column + credit column
Use:
•	side = DR/CR
•	amount = numeric
Because UI and database become simpler.
But both are valid models.
________________________________________
4) Predefined Heads + Auto Dr/Cr (The Right Way)
Now let’s build the best structure.
✅ 4.1 Two Concepts You Must Separate
✅ A) Ledger Head (Account)
Example:
Cash in Hand
✅ B) Template Role (Meaning inside voucher type)
Example:
In Money Transfer voucher, Cash is always “Received From Customer”
So we don’t auto side from ledger nature.
We auto side from voucher type role mapping.
________________________________________
✅ 4.2 The Template System (Professional Level)
A template is a blueprint of a voucher.
It defines:
✅ which ledgers appear
✅ which side they default to
✅ whether they are locked
✅ which lines take user input
✅ which lines are calculated automatically
________________________________________
✅ Template Example: Money Transfer Cash
MT_RECEIPT Template
1.	Cash in Hand → DR → input = Transfer + commission (or full)
2.	Remittance Payable → CR → input = Transfer amount
3.	Commission Income → CR → input = commission
Now staff enters only two numbers:
✅ transfer amount
✅ commission
Software fills everything else.
________________________________________
5) The “Template Engine Tables” (Best Database Design)
✅ 5.1 templates table
Stores master template:
•	template_id
•	voucher_type_id
•	template_name
•	is_active
✅ 5.2 template_lines table
Stores blueprint lines:
•	template_line_id
•	template_id
•	ledger_id
•	default_side (DR/CR)
•	is_fixed_side (TRUE/FALSE)
•	is_required (TRUE/FALSE)
•	amount_rule (INPUT/FIXED/CALCULATED)
•	calc_formula (optional)
✅ This makes templates programmable.
________________________________________
✅ 5.3 Why formula support is powerful?
Example in Jewellery Sale:
GST = total × 3%
So template can auto-split:
•	Sales income
•	GST output
Without staff doing math.
________________________________________
6) Posting Logic (The Heart of the System)
This is what separates “simple software” from “real accounting software”.
✅ 6.1 Posting flow
Step 1: Build voucher object
Collect header + lines.
Step 2: Normalize lines
Convert UI into proper lines:
•	Remove blank
•	Ensure side exists
•	Ensure amount > 0
Step 3: Validation engine
✅ must pass or block saving.
________________________________________
✅ 6.2 Validation engine (Advanced checks)
✅ A) Structural validation
•	voucher type exists
•	minimum 2 lines
•	no duplicate line IDs
•	each line has ledger_id
•	line amount > 0
•	side is DR/CR only
✅ B) Accounting validation
•	total DR == total CR
•	no forbidden ledgers inactive
•	date within open period
✅ C) Business validation (template based)
•	required ledgers must exist
•	side must match if fixed
•	party mandatory if required
Example:
In “Customer Ledger Receipt”, party must be chosen.
________________________________________
✅ 6.3 Voucher numbering (must be concurrency-safe)
Never generate voucher_no on app side.
Do it inside DB transaction:
✅ select sequence row FOR UPDATE
✅ read next_number
✅ create voucher_no
✅ increment next_number
✅ commit
This prevents duplicates in multi-user environment.
________________________________________
✅ 6.4 Atomic Save Rule (Never break books)
Posting must be one transaction:
✅ Insert voucher header
✅ Insert voucher lines
✅ Insert audit log
✅ Commit
If any fails → rollback
________________________________________
7) Audit Trail (Indian compliance ready)
This is extremely important.
Your audit table must store:
✅ Action
✅ User
✅ DateTime
✅ Old value JSON
✅ New value JSON
✅ Reason (for reverse/override)
Examples of actions:
•	CREATE
•	POST
•	REVERSE
•	OVERRIDE_UNLOCK
•	DELETE_ATTEMPT
✅ This makes your software “audit-grade”.
________________________________________
8) Reversal System (Perfect correction method)
Reversal voucher logic:
Take original voucher lines and swap sides:
DR becomes CR
CR becomes DR
Mark original voucher:
status = REVERSED
link reversal voucher ID
✅ Never delete vouchers.
Never directly edit posted vouchers.
________________________________________
9) Reporting Engine (Real accounting reports)
Now deep dive into reporting.
✅ 9.1 Day Book
Simple list:
voucher header + total + type
Filters:
date range, type, ledger, party
________________________________________
✅ 9.2 Ledger Statement (Running balance)
This is the most important report.
For one ledger:
Show all voucher lines affecting it, ordered by date.
Running balance logic:
For Assets & Expenses:
Balance = (opening + DR - CR)
For Liabilities & Income:
Balance = (opening + CR - DR)
✅ Ledger nature decides formula.
________________________________________
✅ 9.3 Trial Balance
Trial balance is the proof system works.
It lists:
each ledger + closing balance
Sum of all DR balances = Sum of all CR balances
If mismatch → system has corruption.
✅ So trial balance is your “health check”.
________________________________________
✅ 9.4 Profit & Loss
Only INCOME and EXPENSE groups:
Profit = Income - Expense
________________________________________
✅ 9.5 Balance Sheet
Assets = Liabilities + Equity
This is built from ledger balances grouped by nature.
________________________________________
10) Handling Parties (Customer/Vendor)
This is how professional software does party accounts.
✅ You have a “Customer Ledger Control” system:
Option A (Simple):
One ledger called “Customer Receivable”
Then party_id tracks the customer.
Option B (Professional):
Every customer is a ledger (Tally style)
✅ Best hybrid:
•	keep “control ledger”
•	store party subledger as party_id
This scales best.
________________________________________
11) Real-World Edge Cases (Most software fails here)
Let’s cover what breaks systems.
________________________________________
✅ Case 1: Partial payments
Example: Sale 10,000, customer paid 2,000
•	Customer Receivable DR 10,000
•	Sales Income CR 10,000
Then receipt:
•	Cash DR 2,000
•	Customer Receivable CR 2,000
Outstanding = 8,000
________________________________________
✅ Case 2: Advance received
Customer gives advance for jewellery.
•	Cash DR 5,000
•	Customer Advance (Liability) CR 5,000
Later sale uses it:
•	Customer Advance DR 5,000
•	Sales/Invoice CR 5,000 (part settlement)
________________________________________
✅ Case 3: Discounts
Discount is expense OR reduction in income.
Correct way:
•	Cash DR (after discount)
•	Discount Allowed DR
•	Sales Income CR (full)
________________________________________
✅ Case 4: GST handling
Professional way:
Sales split into:
•	Sales Income
•	Output GST Payable
Purchases split into:
•	Purchase
•	Input GST Receivable
________________________________________
12) Performance + Data Integrity (Scaling rules)
✅ Use indexes on:
•	vouchers(date)
•	voucher_lines(ledger_id)
•	voucher_lines(party_id)
•	vouchers(branch_id,date)
✅ Never store balances as truth.
Always compute from voucher lines.
You can cache balances for speed but regenerate if needed.
